    "created_at": "2023-09-14T05:10:14Z",
    "updated_at": "2023-09-14T05:10:14Z",
    "body": "> To be honest, I'm wondering if it's some weird permission issue.\r\n\r\nYeah, I'm wondering if Ubuntu 23.04 is doing something funky with the new installer.\r\n\r\nOur script downloads the file to a location in `/tmp` and then immediately attempts to uncompress it, but it does check for a download error, and it seems that none of y'all are getting one.\r\n\r\nIn principle, that means the only way this bug can occur is if the file immediately disappears or becomes unreadable after the download (the message from tar in the OP suggests that it is disappearing) but I don't understand how that could be happening.\r\n\r\nOf course, bugs being what they are, we could also be seeing the manifestation of other strange issues.\r\n\r\nIf anyone is willing to run a test for me, could you try manually downloading and unpacking the binaries in tempdir? For bash/zsh, the commands should be something like:\r\n\r\n```\r\nurl=\"https://github.com/starship/starship/releases/download/v1.16.0/starship-x86_64-unknown-linux-musl.tar.gz\"\r\nfile=\"$(mktemp).tar.gz\"\r\ncurl --fail --silent --location --output $file $url\r\ntar -xzvof $file\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf this works, it should result in a starship binary in your current working directory. If not, I'd like to know if it looks like `curl` is successfully downloading a binary or not.",
