    "created_at": "2024-01-09T14:13:17Z",
    "updated_at": "2024-01-09T14:13:17Z",
    "body": "> Looks like curl is not behaving as expected. It's told to create /tmp/tmp.ouRILl1Dhi.tar.gz but it only creates /tmp/tmp.ouRILl1Dhi. Or am I misunderstanding something here?\r\n\r\nYes: curl isn't creating `/tmp/tmp.ouRILl1Dhi`, mktemp is. Apparently, snapped curl is  blocked from writing to /tmp.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the installer's current use of mktemp exposes the user to a symlink attack:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\nfile=\"$(mktemp).tar.gz\"\r\n# mktemp creates /tmp/tmp.ouRILl1Dhi\r\n\r\n# attacker creates symlink /tmp/tmp.ouRILl1Dhi.tar.gz to (e.g.) /etc/passwd\r\n\r\ncurl -o $file $url\r\n# curl writes to /etc/passwd via /tmp/tmp.ouRILl1Dhi.tar.gz symlink\r\n```\r\n\r\nmktemp is intended to atomically generate and reserve a unique filename. Deriving a different filename from mktemp's output defeats that.\r\n\r\nTo fix this, ask mktemp to create the file you actually want to use:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\nfile=\"$(mktemp tmp.XXXXXXXXXX.tar.gz)\"\r\n```",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "pin": null,
